### Static Members in C#

Static members belong to the type itself, not to any specific instance. They are shared across all instances.

### Static Fields

```csharp
public class Counter
{
    public static int TotalCount = 0;

    public Counter()
    {
        TotalCount++;
    }
}
```

### Static Methods

```csharp
public class MathUtility
{
    public static int Add(int a, int b) => a + b;
    public static int Max(int a, int b) => a > b ? a : b;
}

// Called on the type, not an instance
int result = MathUtility.Add(5, 3);
```

### Static Properties

```csharp
public class AppConfig
{
    public static string AppName { get; } = "MyApp";
    public static string Version { get; private set; } = "1.0.0";
}
```

### Static Classes

All members must be static. Cannot be instantiated:

```csharp
public static class FileHelper
{
    public static string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);
    public static void WriteAllText(string path, string content) => File.WriteAllText(path, content);
}
```

### Static Constructor

Runs once before any static member is accessed or any instance is created:

```csharp
public class Database
{
    public static readonly string ConnectionString;

    static Database()
    {
        ConnectionString = "Server=localhost;Database=MyDB;";
        Console.WriteLine("Static constructor called");
    }
}
```

### Static vs Instance Members

| Aspect | Static | Instance |
|--------|--------|----------|
| Belongs to | Type | Object |
| Memory | One per type | One per instance |
| Access | `ClassName.Member` | `object.Member` |
| `this` keyword | Not accessible | Accessible |
| Lifetime | App domain lifetime | Object lifetime |

### Extension Methods

All extension methods must be static:

```csharp
public static class StringExtensions
{
    public static bool IsPalindrome(this string str)
    {
        return str.SequenceEqual(str.Reverse());
    }
}
```

### Static Local Functions (C# 8+)

Cannot capture variables from enclosing scope:

```csharp
int Calculate(int x, int y)
{
    static int Multiply(int a, int b) => a * b;
    return Multiply(x, y);
}
```

> **Key Point:** Static members are accessed through the class name, not an instance. Use static members for utility functions, shared state, and singleton patterns. Static constructors run once per type at an indeterminate time before the type is first used.

### Common Static Members in .NET

```csharp
Console.WriteLine();     // Static method
Math.PI;                 // Static property
int.Parse("123");       // Static method
String.IsNullOrEmpty();  // Static method
DateTime.Now;            // Static property
```

codeExample:
using System;

public static class TemperatureConverter
{
    public static double CelsiusToFahrenheit(double celsius)
        => (celsius * 9 / 5) + 32;

    public static double FahrenheitToCelsius(double fahrenheit)
        => (fahrenheit - 32) * 5 / 9;
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        double tempC = 25;
        double tempF = TemperatureConverter.CelsiusToFahrenheit(tempC);
        Console.WriteLine($"{tempC}C = {tempF}F");

        double backToC = TemperatureConverter.FahrenheitToCelsius(tempF);
        Console.WriteLine($"{tempF}F = {backToC:F1}C");
    }
}
